    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI use `vim.ui_attach` to draw a custom command line/popup menu, hiding the default ones. Now, if ui2 is enabled, I end up with two simultaneous cmdlines.\n\nBefore enabling ui2 (same behavior as 0.11 and before):\n\n<img width=\"1290\" height=\"748\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1388d256-79e3-4e53-a618-6ab71987276e\" />\n\nAfter enabling ui2:\n\n<img width=\"1283\" height=\"728\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/1b843dc2-a35d-4cee-a17a-a427faada02e\" />\n\nI don't use Noice.nvim, but I have found an issue there reporting the same issue with their ext_cmdline as well (https://github.com/folke/noice.nvim/issues/1201).\n\nChanging the options passed to ui2 does not change the result.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim --clean\n:lua vim.ui_attach(vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"newNS\"), { ext_cmline = true }, function() end)\n(Cmdline should no longer be visible when typing commands)\n:lua require(\"vim._core.ui2\").enable({})\n(Cmdline is once again visible when typing commands)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nWhen ui2 is enabled and ext_cmdline is attached with `vim.ui_attach`, the default command line should no longer appear as it's now handled by the attached handlers.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNot relevant\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11 Pro, Version 10.0.26200 Build 26200\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nTested on Windows Terminal v1.23.20211.0 and Wezterm 20240203-110809-5046fc22\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nNot set\n\n### Installation\n\nWinget",
